⁶ It was reserved for Elwert († 1865) to develop most thor- oughly the theory of inspiration based upon principles laid down by Schleiermacher. This view supposes the apostles to have been inspired, only in so far as the spirit works in them a faith by which they appropriated to themselves the revelation of Christ, and so far as from this, by means of faith, in the natural way of reflection, their religious ideas and conceptions found develop— ment.' ¹

The differences between this later and the earlier idea of inspi- ration, are thus summed up.²
